Overall, the cohort showed several statistically robust treatment/biomarker-like signals despite the opaque feature labels. The strongest supported conclusions were probability-scale main effects for a small group of features, persistence of several of those effects in full multivariable adjustment, and non-additive response heterogeneity in selected feature-defined subgroups. The most convincing interaction patterns were the binary-binary pairs listed above because they were directly interpretable as differences in observed response rates across four patient subgroups. Continuous interaction findings were statistically weaker and should be interpreted as exploratory unless replicated in an external cohort or a prespecified model.

 succeeded in 1040ms:
Dataset ds001_aml contained 50000 patients and one binary outcome, objective_response. The overall response rate was 0.1875. I decoded the local Parquet file and tested main effects, subgroup heterogeneity, and interactions using response-rate contrasts and linear probability models; p-values are exploratory and mostly unadjusted unless explicitly described as adjusted.

Main effects: feature_027 had the strongest monotone association. Response fell from 0.231 at level 0 to 0.174 at level 1 and 0.129 at level 2, with an effect of -0.0522 per level (p=4.40e-92). The strongest binary positive main effects were feature_025 (effect 0.0674, p=6.82e-64), feature_015 (effect 0.0559, p=1.75e-53), and feature_023 (effect 0.0535, p=3.69e-49). Negative binary main effects were feature_001 (effect -0.0229, p=1.34e-6) and feature_032 (effect -0.0242, p=1.43e-5). Feature_044 showed no meaningful main effect per 10 units (effect -0.00024, p=0.882).

Continuous features: feature_004, feature_031, feature_059, feature_033, and feature_053 all showed significant univariable associations. The directions were lower response with higher feature_004 (effect -0.0052 per unit), lower response with higher feature_031 (effect -0.0075 per 10 units), higher response with higher feature_059 (effect 0.0179 per unit), lower response with higher feature_033 (effect -0.00086 per unit), and lower response with higher feature_053 (effect -0.0025 per 10 units). In the extended adjusted model, these directions remained significant except feature_044, which stayed null.

The most important interaction pattern involved feature_015, feature_025, and feature_023. Pairwise screens initially showed large positive interactions among these variables, especially feature_015 x feature_025 (DID 0.1926, p=2.06e-118), feature_025 x feature_023 (DID 0.1908, p=9.78e-117), and feature_015 x feature_023 (DID 0.1528, p=3.97e-91). Subgroup testing refined this: feature_015 had almost no effect when feature_025=0 (effect -0.0016, p=0.694) but a large positive effect when feature_025=1 (effect 0.1910, p=2.27e-152).

The refined multivariable interaction model showed that the apparent pairwise effects were largely driven by a three-way pattern. Patients with feature_015=1, feature_025=1, and feature_023=1 had response 0.633 (n=2401), versus 0.165 among all other patients, an absolute difference of 0.468. In a model containing all three main effects, all pairwise terms, the three-way term, feature_001, feature_032, and feature_027, the three-way coefficient was 0.4624 (p=9.78e-202), while the pairwise terms became nonsignificant. This suggests a high-response subgroup defined by simultaneous positivity for all three features rather than three independent pairwise synergies.

Negative-effect heterogeneity was also present. feature_001 attenuated the feature_025 association (interaction -0.0958, p=1.09e-20), feature_032 attenuated the feature_025 association (interaction -0.0755, p=6.70e-10), and feature_032 attenuated the feature_015 association (interaction -0.0458, p=5.97e-5). The two negative main-effect features feature_001 and feature_032 did not show evidence of an additional negative interaction with each other (interaction 0.0181, p=0.237).

Subgroup checks across feature_027 did not show statistically significant modification of the feature_015 effect by feature_027 (interaction -0.0044, p=0.404); feature_015 was positive at all feature_027 levels. Nominal continuous-by-binary interactions were detected for feature_044 by feature_066 (slope difference 0.0129 per 10 units, p=0.0039) and feature_053 by feature_068 (slope difference -0.0077 per 10 units, p=0.0061), but these were weaker exploratory findings.

Overall conclusion: objective_response in this cohort is dominated by a strong low-response gradient across feature_027, independent continuous adverse associations involving feature_004, feature_031, feature_033, and feature_053, a positive continuous association with feature_059, and a striking high-response subgroup where feature_015, feature_025, and feature_023 are all present. The strongest treatment-biomarker-like relationship is the three-feature interaction; isolated positivity for only one or two of those features does not reproduce the same high response rate.

 succeeded in 1044ms:
Dataset ds001_aml contains 50,000 AML patient records. The outcome objective_response was positive in 9,375 patients (18.75%). I decoded the local Parquet file and ran 25 iterative analyses using two-proportion tests, linear probability trends, additive interaction contrasts, and a robust-SE adjusted linear probability model.

The strongest main-effect signals were favorable binary features feature_025, feature_015, and feature_023. Objective response was 23.5% versus 16.7% for feature_025 (risk difference +6.7 percentage points, p<1e-10), 22.1% versus 16.5% for feature_015 (+5.6 pp, p<1e-10), and 22.0% versus 16.6% for feature_023 (+5.3 pp, p<1e-10). Adverse main effects included feature_027 level 2 versus levels 0/1 (-6.7 pp, p<1e-10), feature_001 (-2.3 pp, p=3.1e-6), feature_032 (-2.4 pp, p=3.2e-5), high feature_004, and high feature_031.

Interaction analyses changed the interpretation substantially. The three favorable binary features were not merely additive: feature_025 x feature_015 had an additive interaction of +19.3 pp, feature_025 x feature_023 +19.1 pp, and feature_015 x feature_023 +15.3 pp, all highly significant. Triple-positive patients for feature_025, feature_015, and feature_023 had a 45.3% response rate versus 17.1% for all others (+28.2 pp, p<1e-10). The formal three-way additive contrast was also strongly positive (+46.2 pp, p<1e-10), so the triple-positive subgroup exceeded expectations even after accounting for lower-order response-rate contrasts.

Resistance-like heterogeneity was also present. feature_001 and feature_032 attenuated the favorable feature_025 association: feature_025 x feature_001 had a -9.6 pp additive interaction and feature_025 x feature_032 had a -7.5 pp interaction. Similar attenuation was seen for feature_015 x feature_001 and feature_023 x feature_032. In the adjusted model, the major favorable pairwise interactions and the adverse feature_025 interactions remained strong; the independent adjusted main effects for feature_001 and feature_032 were no longer significant, while feature_027, feature_004, and feature_031 retained adverse adjusted associations.

Some weaker exploratory findings were not robust enough to treat as central. feature_005 had a positive univariate risk difference of +1.6 pp but p=0.056, and feature_074 had a negative difference of -1.2 pp but p=0.069. A feature_005 x feature_013 negative interaction was also not significant. Exploratory pairwise screens found additional smaller interactions such as feature_040 x feature_046 and feature_050 x feature_071, but the dominant and most coherent structure involved feature_025, feature_015, feature_023, feature_001, and feature_032.

Overall, objective response in this AML cohort appears driven by a strong treatment/biomarker-like interaction pattern among three favorable opaque features, with separate adverse effects from feature_027 and continuous feature_004/feature_031 and interaction-based attenuation by feature_001 and feature_032. Because the feature labels are anonymized, the findings should be interpreted as statistical patterns rather than named clinical mechanisms.

